Corrupted beyond redemption
My friend Boris was leaving my place, corrupted.
I suggested to him not to drive.
He asked me why.
"You have been drinking," I said, "are you not afraid of the police?"
Boris replied, "no, I possess a document featuring Benjamin Franklin, it's always useful."
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped beside it.
Obviously, I knew the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris would encounter an officer who wasn't corrupted.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to join the traffic police unit, you must buy your boss's silence."
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The idiots who try to do things by the book get bogged down in red tape.
"For $100, you can drive in town without brakes!"
Corruption and fund diversion have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom none are offered, according to Boris.
Corruption thrives in most institutions, and the fight against it always ends in a disaster or abandonment.
Everyone, from the police to prosecutors, customs officials, and even the Kremlin, is immune nowhere.
Recently, I was visiting a village of dachas in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a luxurious place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious houses decorated with so little taste, I wondered who owned them and heard that one belonged to an assistant mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and yet another to the son of Moscow's prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax service official.
Corruption now represents a more serious threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted so long if it had not been fought by corrupt generals, officers, civil servants, and police who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a shuttle bus traveling from Grozny to Moscow, the same bus that transported 120 kilograms of explosives used in the siege of the Dubrovka theater, where so many victims perished during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A passenger covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A pointless precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times during his journey, always for the same reason.
A policeman came to ask him, "do you know the price?" and the driver replied, "of course, I know it," paying the bribe before getting back on the bus.
Without the bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, or entire days for the journey.
The war against Chechnya continues without end not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al-Qaeda and all "international terrorism," but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes and thieves, who first tax or simply steal from Chechen civilians, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide maps indicating where the minefields are, and supply rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, the terrorists used weapons bought from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gunshops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers who fight the rebels have ammunition stocks, from where the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not just weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no fight has been launched against this scourge.
To tackle corruption more harshly?
This would merely increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are corrupt themselves.
Thus, those referred to as "ordinary people" view this phenomenon with indulgence.
They say of their mayor, "Yes, of course, he steals, but look at all he's done for the city!"
Ordinary people do not like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the inspector both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The inspector stopped her, saying that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy a military clerk and he will remove your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is around to bribe the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister under Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When Tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Over the centuries since, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption might leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the advancement of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
